# Engram Local Memory

## 2026-06-12 - Codex synchronized GitHub-facing docs with Swift product state

- Updated `README.md`, `docs/mcp-tools.md`, `docs/mcp-swift.md`,
  `docs/roadmap.md`, and `docs/PRIVACY.md` to match the current shipped Swift
  macOS app plus Swift MCP helper.
- Current docs now state: active MCP surface has 28 tools; Swift search is
  keyword-only; legacy `semantic`/`hybrid` search requests are compatibility
  inputs that degrade to keyword with a warning; MCP `live_sessions` is
  intentionally unavailable; app/service IPC still has local live-session
  scanning; exports are written under `~/.engram/exports/`; insights are
  text/FTS-first without product-side embeddings.
- `docs/mcp-swift.md` now documents supported initialize protocol versions
  `2024-11-05`, `2025-03-26`, `2025-06-18`, and `2025-11-25`, plus the
  28-tool stale-helper troubleshooting threshold.
- README/privacy provider wording now matches the Swift product: summary
  generation uses an OpenAI-compatible chat provider via `aiApiKey`; title
  generation uses `titleProvider`/`titleApiKey` and supports Ollama, OpenAI, or
  a custom OpenAI-compatible endpoint.
- Corrected `MCPToolRegistry`'s `get_context.task` schema description from
  semantic search to related context lookup. This was documentation/schema text
  only, not a behavior change.

## 2026-06-12 - Codex fixed EngramService startup crash and high CPU scan

- Trigger: live EngramService was repeatedly rescanning at high CPU and crash
  reports showed `Database was not used on the correct thread` on
  `GRDB.DatabasePool.writer`, faulting in observability retention pruning.
- Follow-up scalability PR1: added `file_index_state` in
  `EngramMigrations.createOrUpdateBaseSchema`, plus `FileIndexStat`,
  `FileIndexState`, and `FileIndexDecision` in
  `EngramCoreWrite/Indexing/IndexingWriteSink.swift`. `EngramDatabaseWriter`
  now exposes `knownFileIndexStates` and `upsertFileIndexState`.
- Follow-up behavior: `SwiftIndexer.scanSnapshots` consults file-index state
  before parsing direct file locators, records terminal parse failures so they
  are skipped until the file changes, records retryable failures with
  `retry_after`, and writes success state only after the session batch upsert
  reports a non-failure result.
- Failure policy: `lineTooLarge`, `fileTooLarge`, `messageLimitExceeded`, and
  `unsupportedVirtualLocator` are terminal. `malformedJSON` remains retryable
  to avoid tombstoning partial JSONL writes.
- Follow-up tests:
  `testFileIndexDecisionSkipsTerminalFailureUntilFileChanges`,
  `testFileIndexDecisionBacksOffMalformedFailureBeforeRetryAfter`,
  `testFileIndexDecisionSchemaVersionMismatchForcesFull`,
  `testStartupIndexCachesTerminalParseFailureAndSkipsNextRun`, and
  `testStartupIndexSkipsRetryFailureBeforeRetryAfter`.
- Follow-up verification: the focused file-index/startup/recent-index test set
  exited 0; `xcodebuild build -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme
  EngramServiceCore -destination 'platform=macOS' CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO
  -quiet` exited 0; `git diff --check` exited 0.
- Follow-up deployment note: the `file_index_state` PR1 was initially left
  undeployed, then shipped together with PR2 in local build `20260612060821`.
- Follow-up residual risk: broader `SchemaCompatibilityTests` and full
  `IndexerParityTests` still crash under the known duplicate-GRDB XCTest host
  issue on this machine. Append-only offset parsing is still deferred.
- Follow-up scalability PR2 profiling: a live 9.6 MB Codex JSONL transcript
  took about 0.006s to read and 0.268s to parse with Foundation
  `JSONSerialization`, producing 4,931 parsed records and 3,350 response
  records in 0.70s wall time. This does not explain multi-minute CPU by itself,
  so append-only offset parsing remains deferred until broader scan evidence
  justifies it.
- Follow-up scalability PR2 behavior: when startup all-scan skips a direct file
  locator because legacy `sessions` indexed state already proves the locator is
  known, `SwiftIndexer` now backfills `file_index_state=ok` for that locator.
  This migrates old libraries into the new manifest without reparsing every
  historical file.
- Follow-up scalability PR2 test:
  `IndexerParityTests.testStartupIndexBackfillsFileIndexStateWhenSkippingKnownSessionLocator`
  failed before implementation and passed afterward.
- Follow-up scalability PR2 verification: focused file-index/startup/recent
  tests exited 0; `xcodebuild build -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme
  EngramServiceCore -destination 'platform=macOS' CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO
  -quiet` exited 0; `git diff --check` exited 0.
- Follow-up scalability PR2 local deploy: `macos/scripts/build-release.sh
  --local-only` exported
  `/Users/bing/-Code-/engram/macos/build/EngramExport/Engram.app` version
  `0.1.0`, build `20260612060821`, with full Developer ID verification.
  `macos/scripts/deploy-local.sh macos/build/EngramExport/Engram.app`
  installed it to `/Applications/Engram.app`.
- Follow-up scalability PR2 live verification: the first startup populated the
  live `file_index_state` manifest (`ok=4549`, `retry=22`) and then settled to
  low CPU. A second app/service restart at `2026-06-12 14:14:25 +0800`
  verified the cached path: both `Engram` and `EngramService` were 0.0% CPU at
  15s and remained 0.0% CPU at about 90s. Logs after the second restart had no
  `session parse failed`, `session index error`, `Database was not used`,
  fatal, fault, or error entries, and no new `EngramService*.ips` crash report
  appeared.
- Root cause: `EngramServiceCore` owned the retention implementation and used a
  `GRDB.Database` handle produced by `EngramCoreWrite`'s database pool. With
  duplicate GRDB framework copies loaded, that crossed GRDB runtime ownership
  checks.
- Fix: moved `ObservabilityRetention` into `macos/EngramCoreWrite` and added
  `EngramDatabaseWriter.pruneObservabilityRetention(...)`; changed
  `EngramServiceRunner.runObservabilityRetention` to call that writer API from
  inside `ServiceWriterGate.performWriteCommand`.
- Regression: `ObservabilityRetentionTests.testPruneRunsInsideServiceWriterGateWrite`
  covers the startup/gated-write path that previously crashed; existing prune
  count and bounded-batch tests now use the writer API.
- Follow-on root cause: after the retention crash was fixed and the app was
  redeployed, startup `indexAllSessions` still reparsed known Codex transcript
  files that had grown after their stored `indexed_at`. The live Codex JSONL was
  about 8.6 MB, so every restart spent minutes in `SwiftIndexer.scanSnapshots`
  -> `CodexAdapter.streamMessages`.
- Follow-on fix: startup/all indexing now skips known direct file locators, so
  the all-scan only fills missing historical locators; recent/periodic indexing
  still handles recently changed files.
- Follow-on regression tests:
  `IndexerParityTests.testStartupIndexAllSkipsUnchangedFileLocatorsOnSecondRun`,
  `testStartupIndexAllDefersKnownHotFileLocators`, and
  `testStartupIndexAllSkipsKnownModifiedFileLocators`. Existing recent-index
  tests still cover parsing changed files outside the startup all-scan.
- Deployment: `macos/scripts/build-release.sh --local-only` produced
  `macos/build/EngramExport/Engram.app` version `0.1.0`, build
  `20260612024348`, with full Developer ID verification; `macos/scripts/deploy-local.sh
  macos/build/EngramExport/Engram.app` installed it to
  `/Applications/Engram.app` and the app was restarted.
- Verification:
  - `git diff --check` exited 0.
  - `xcodebuild test -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme EngramServiceCore
    -destination 'platform=macOS' CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO
    -only-testing:EngramServiceCoreTests/ObservabilityRetentionTests -quiet`
    exited 0.
  - Focused `EngramCoreTests` startup/recent-index tests exited 0.
  - `xcodebuild build -project macos/Engram.xcodeproj -scheme EngramServiceCore
    -destination 'platform=macOS' CODE_SIGNING_ALLOWED=NO -quiet` exited 0.
  - Final live restart check: at 10s `EngramService` showed the expected startup
    spike; at about 90s it was 4.0% CPU; at about 130s it was 1.5% CPU. No new
    `EngramService-*.ips` appeared, and the final 30s log window had no
    `session parse failed` or `session index error`.
- Residual risk: full `EngramServiceCore` suite was not rerun after the focused
  regressions because an earlier full run hung in Xcode test launch. Historical
  malformed/empty Codex JSONL files remain on disk and can still log during the
  first seconds of startup until a separate failed-locator cache is added.

